Riddle solved: That's why we can't tickle ourselves
A kind of brake in the cerebrum prevents people from tickling themselves. This is what scientists from the Humboldt University in Berlin found this with the help of experiments on rats, as they announced on Thursday evening. Progress has also been made on why children are so strongly defending themselves against tickling, only to demand more.
Finally, it has also been shown why the approach of a tickling hand alone triggers laughter before the touch. This lies on a low-lying layer in the cerebrum, which already triggers the laughter when they were tickled up.
According to the data, previous research showed that rats react with "laughter" in the ultrasound area when they are tickled by humans. This "laughter" is conveyed by the part of the cerebral cortex, which serves the central processing of haptic perception.
Laughter is suppressed during self-contact
Until now, it has been assumed that the brain could distinguish between self-touching and touch by others - so people cannot tickle themselves. However, the Berlin researchers now found in the experiments on the rats that the laughter as well as the activity of the area in question are suppressed during a self-contact. This is also true when living beings clean themselves. However, during the touch of others and tickling by the scientists, the activity in the brain and the impulse were amplified to laugh.
However, if the self-contact and touching by others at the same time were also suppressed. This suggests that the rat's brain cannot distinguish between self-touching and contact by others. The new findings suggested that people cannot tickle themselves because self-contact activated a brake in the cerebrum.
The rats were also trained to tickle themselves. They sometimes abandoned this initiation in the experiment prematurely, showing flight behaviour or frightness. This ambivalence is the same as the behavior of the children. The ambivalence of tickling is a behavioural reaction that is equal to rats and people.
