Attention: Smartphone NIE wireless charging
Practical but harmful
Inductive technology via Qi standard is extremely practical, but should not be used.
Since several new smartphones have finally come on the market, which support wireless charging and sell very well - especially the new iPhone 11 models, we would like to recall another study from the beginning of July. Wireless charging of mobile devices is extremely convenient, but not necessarily recommended.
Higher temperature adds battery to
Researchers warn against wireless charging of smartphones. According to the findings of the Univerity of Warwick, this is extremely harmful to the devices. The reason for this is the significantly greater heat development. If you load a mobile phone normally by cable, the battery heats up to 27 degrees within three hours. When charging, the researchers have always measured more than 30 degrees even when the smartphone is perfectly aligned on the charging pad. If the mobile phone is slightly next to the coil, the temperature rises even higher. In addition, the wattage of the charging pad also increases, which in turn drives up the power consumption.
Capacity and Lifetime
According to researchers, the temperature for the durability of batteries is a decisive factor. Every single degree plays a role. When charging with higher temperatures, the battery not only absorbs capacity, but also does not last so long overall. The service life is therefore lower. The researchers therefore advise you to always charge the smartphone using a cable. Since a battery replacement for modern smartphones is always associated with high costs, this should be a helpful tip. Apple has even increased the cost of recovering batteries - for all iPhones.
Practically
The technology is extremely convenient: Simply putting the device on a corresponding charging pad - these are now even installed in many restaurants, airports, hotels and cars - and the battery is charged without the hassle of cable clothing and laborious connector bumblebee. Since Qi (is inductive energy transmission) is a global standard enforced, in which Apple even participates exceptionally, there are hardly any restrictions. Nevertheless, according to the researchers, the technology should only be applied in exceptional cases.
